description: From Middle English thrucchen (“to push, rush”), from Old English þryċċan (“to push, press, trample on, crush”), from Proto-West Germanic *þrukkijan, from Proto-Germanic *þrukkijaną (“to press”). Cognate with West Frisian drukke (“to press”), Dutch drukken (“to press, squeeze”), German drücken (“to press, push, squeeze”), Swedish trycka (“to press, push, squeeze”).

entries.meaning: (caving, climbing (sport)) An obstacle overcome by thrutching; an act of thrutching (See verb #5)
(UK dialectal, Northern England) A narrow gorge or ravine.

verbs.description: thrutch (third-person singular simple present thrutches, present participle thrutching, simple past and past participle thrutched)

entries.meaning: (caving, climbing (sport)) To push, press, or squeeze into a place; move sideways or vertically in an upright position by wriggling the body against opposing rock surfaces. Compare chimney.
examples: I thrutched up the final crack to a small pinnacle.
